# Highest GDP Growth
In my first query, we need a way to select the maximum `indicatorValue (GDP_growth_value)` with regards to `countryName`. To do this, we create an inner query grouped by `countryName`, where we retrieve the maximum value of the `indicatorValue`, but also making sure that `indicatorCode='NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG'`. With this query, we inner join it with the original table, but only where `indicatorValue` and `countryName` of the inner queries match. This query has a problem in that some countries have multiple max indicatorCode, and may add noise to data. In another attempt, I added a window function to give a rank to all countryNames, ordered by year descending, and with another outer query to select only where `rank=1`. This way, only the latest data will be displayed in the table.

Spark runtime is faster than Hive. Spark runtime was 1 minute 8 seconds, compared to Hive which took 2 mins 40 seconds.

%spark.sql
SELECT DISTINCT orig.indicatorValue AS GDP_growth_value,
        orig.year AS year,
        orig.countryName as countryName
FROM wdi_csv_parquet AS orig
INNER JOIN (
SELECT  parq.indicatorValue AS GDP_growth_value, 
        parq.year AS year, 
        parq.countryName AS countryname,
        RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY parq.countryname ORDER BY parq.year DESC) as rank
FROM wdi_csv_parquet AS parq 
INNER JOIN (SELECT max(indicatorValue) AS indicatorValue, countryName
			FROM wdi_csv_parquet
			WHERE indicatorCode = 'NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG'
			GROUP BY countryName) AS maxVal
WHERE maxVal.countryName = parq.countryName and maxVal.indicatorValue = parq.indicatorValue
) AS ranked
WHERE   orig.indicatorValue = ranked.gdp_growth_value
AND     orig.year = ranked.year
AND     orig.countryName = ranked.countryName
AND     ranked.rank = 1

# Columnar File Optimization
Parquet file only takes up 137.2 M of disk space compared to regular row based storage `wdi_opencsv_text` took around 1.7 G of data. This is because parquet data is stored column-wise - data in columns are stored adjacently to each other, which along with having more homogenous data allows for more compression techniques to be used. Therefore parquet files save more disk space relative to row-oriented storage.

In addition to this, the parquet query took around 9 seconds relative to the row-oriented query which took 1 min 22 seconds. This significant gain in performance is likely due to the query we are feeding are column oriented - we need to scan 2 columns, which is what parquet storage is optimized for.

# Comparing OpenCSVSerde vs Row Format Delimited Fields Serde

This is likely because OpenCSVSerde must process each row of data to ensure that the data is being parsed correctly whereas using Row Format Delimited can simply split by commas, making it much faster without much processing needed.

## Creating and populating wdi_csv_text
To store the data from Google Storage locally, we first create external table wdi_csv_text associated with file location: 'hdfs:///user/rsa-key-20191121/hive/wdi/wdi_csv_text'.
After this we populate it with contents from original Google Storage with `INSERT OVERWRITE` command from wdi_gs
## Cache Observations
Counting number of countryNames on first attempt took 29[sec]. On second attempt, it took 19[sec]. After clearing worker nodes cache, and reattempting, it took 30[sec]. The cause of this is because on first attempt, the cache is empty, therefore data has to be sent from disk to memory to local cache for both nodes - a speedup occurs in the second attempt because each of the worker nodes have their cache full with data from previous run. After clearing cache of both workers, situtation returns to case where cache is empty and causes the run time to increase
## Bash vs HDFS
Took 34 seconds to read on bash compared to around 29-30 seconds with cleared cache on Hive, and 19 seconds with filled cache on Hive. In theory Hive should be much faster because it has 2 worker nodes working in parallel to read incoming data. Hadoop's advantage may not be pronounced because it is optimized to work with very large datasets, and 1.8GB size is not very large.
